# Insights  {#insights}

This report synthesises the past 90 days of GA4 analytics, internal site search data, Google organic search queries, AI referral traffic (ChatGPT/Copilot), landing page behaviour, and January 2026 user feedback (9,295 usefulness ratings; 708 free-text comments) to identify the highest-priority design opportunities for improving how Buckinghamshire residents find and access council services, as well as what we could prioritise as key journeys for the upcoming design sprints.

### **Key Finding:** 

Residents are overwhelmingly visiting the site for five service areas \- waste & bins, council tax, planning, school admissions, and roads/parking. They are consistently failing to complete tasks on hub/contact pages that offer broad navigation rather than clear action routes.

### **Key Numbers:**

* Total users (in 90 days) \- 446,914  
* New vs returning users \- 84% new / 16% returning  
* Organic Search (primary channel) \- 70% of users

#### **Seasonal Usage Insights:**

When looked at across the year, certain seasonal patterns emerge. This could mean that users might benefit from being served information based on these patterns at different times across the year based on what they are looking for.

**Q1 (January–March) \- Admissions & Account Activity**: 

* School admissions dominate. The January deadline for primary school applications creates a sharp spike \- the primary school application journey (/apply-for-a-primary-school-place/ → /find-schools-to-apply-for/ → /submit-your-school-preferences/) shows strong sequential traffic and a notably long engagement time, indicating residents working through the form.   
* Grammar school registration also appears here.   
* Secondary school allocation results land in March, driving a second admissions spike (checking vacancies, in-year transfers).  
* Council tax starts warming up from February as residents anticipate new bills.

**Q2 (April–June) \- Council Tax, Garden Waste & Elections**: 

* This is the busiest quarter for council tax. New bills go out in April, which drives the manage/pay/contact cluster.   
* Garden waste subscription renewal is a major Q2 peak \- likely 60–70% concentrated between March to May as the spring/summer growing starts and residents may want to reactivate. DIY waste permits spike strongly too.  
* May 2025 had Buckinghamshire Council elections. The elections pages represented a one-off spike that inflated overall Q2 traffic for 2025 \- worth discounting when comparing to 2026 projections.

**Q3 (July–September) \- Summer, Leisure & Grammar School Prep**: 

* School term dates get heavy lookups before summer break. Black Park and leisure/parks pages spike.   
* Grammar school 11+ registration opens in September, driving early admissions traffic.  
* Bin collection remains steady year-round (it's the highest-traffic transactional need regardless of season) but DIY waste permits stay elevated through summer.

**Q4 (October–December) \- Secondary Admissions, Christmas Disruption**: 

* October is the secondary school application deadline. The ‘/apply-for-a-secondary-school-place/’ journey (including ‘/choose-which-schools-to-apply-for/’ and ‘/submit-your-school-application/’) peaks sharply.   
* Grammar school transfer test results and the selection review process also generate significant October traffic.  
* December is heavily dominated by service disruption queries, especially for the waste and recycling service area. The Christmas bin dates page could be a good candidate for a prominent seasonal banner or homepage callout that gets activated each November. 

**Year-round high volume areas, no strong seasonality**:

* Bin collection day checker \- consistent throughout the year, slightly lower in December/January  
* Planning applications \- steady, slight dip in summer  
* Council tax manage/pay \- peaks April but never fully quiet  
* Contact us \- high all year

Responses were received from a third of councils (33 per cent), as such, the results of the survey should not be taken to be more widely representative of the views of all councils. Rather, they are a snapshot of the views of this particular group of respondents.
